Good Plot

Plot showing the distribution of Scores in Autism Spectrum Quotient Short (AQ-S), Toronto Alexithymia Scale (TAS) and Reading the Mind in the Eyes test (RMET)

# Add TAS variable
totals <- totals |>
  mutate(TAS = if_else(tas.total >54, "Alexithymia", "No Alexithymia"))

totals$TAS <- factor(totals$TAS)

plot_good <- ggscatter(totals, x = "rmet.correct", y = "aq.total", 
                          palette = "jco", facet.by = "TAS",
                          add = "reg.line") + geom_jitter(position = position_jitter(width = 0.05), alpha = 0.5, size = 0.005, shape = 16, show.legend = FALSE) 

# Add labels
plot_good <- plot_good +
  labs(
    x = "RMET Score",
    y = "AQ-S Score",
    title = "Autism Spectrum Quotient and Reading the Mind in the Eye Test Score",
    subtitle = "For people with high and low scores on the Toronto Alexithymia Scale",
    caption = "Source: https://osf.io/6hy95"
  )
print(plot_good)

Reasons why this is a good plot: - The scatter plot allows to visualize the relationship between the Autism Spectrum Quotient (AQ) score (x = aq.total) and the Reading the Mind in the Eyes test (RMET) score (y = rmet.correct). Putting these variables in comparison makes sense, since one can expect a relationship. - In addition, the plot is faceted by the TAS Score (I set the Cut-Off 54 for Alexithymia), allowing us to compare the scatter plots side by side. - The addition of jitter helps avoid overplotting, making it easier to see the density of points. - The regression lines help to visualize the trend of the correlation at first sight. - Proper labeling and legends make the plot more informative. - The title is long but informative - The source is added at the bottom right hand corner - There is no color added since it is not necessary in this context (the alexithymia/no alexithymia distinction is clear because of the facets) - however one could add colours for aesthetics:) -

Bad Plot

Plot showing the relationship of ethnicity, the score in the Imposing Memory Task (IMT) and the level of reported comfort when viewing eye stimuli

plot_bad <- ggplot(totals, aes(x = imt.correct, y = comfort, color = ethnicity)) +
  geom_point(size = 5, alpha = 0.5) + 
  labs(title = "Bad Plot with Inappropriate Choices") +
  geom_text(aes(label = ID), vjust = 1, hjust = 0.75) +
  theme_minimal()  


# Print the bad plot
print(plot_bad)

Reasons why this is a bad plot: - A scatter plot (geom_point()) is used, but it does not convey any meaningful information. The plot shows the relationship between the variables imt.correct (score of the IMT) and comfort (reported level of comfort when being presented with eye stimuli for the RMET) despite there beeing no reason to assume a relationship. The density of the jitter points is unclear because of the coloring.
- There are no axis labels (xlab() and ylab()) or a legend (labs(color = )) to provide context for the variables. The axis therefore carry the name of the column in the dataset (i.e.imt.correct) which doesnt look nice and is confusing to the viewer. - Color is mapped to the ethnicity variable, but the coding in numbers (1-16) remains unexplained, the colors do not convey any meaningful information and they overlap in the plot. - The jitter points are unnecessarily labelled with the ID numbers but they are not legible as they too overlap. They are set slightly off to the left which looks unsettling and doesnt aid the legibility. - The title doesnt convey any meaningful information.
